summary: This is an FBI Criminal Investigative Division briefing document assessing the performance and threat levels of the FBI New York field office's Crimes Against Children (CAC) and Human Trafficking (HT) programs for FY23. It notes that NY's HT program is a model and is working on high-profile cases including Epstein, NXIVM, and OneTaste.

persons.name: James Smith
persons.context: Addressed in the briefing header, indicating the document is directed to him.

persons.name: Seamus Clarke
persons.context: Identified as the PCOR (Program Coordinator) for both the Crimes Against Children and Human Trafficking programs in the FBI New York field office.

events.title: FBI NY Human Trafficking Program Assessment
events.description: The FBI New York field office's Human Trafficking program is assessed as a Band III threat and is noted for working on the highest-profile HT cases in the FBI, including Epstein, NXIVM, and OneTaste.

events.title: FBI NY Crimes Against Children Program Assessment
events.description: The FBI New York field office's Crimes Against Children program is assessed as a Band II threat, focusing on CSAM production, sextortion, online enticement, and travelers. It opened 88 new investigations.

locations: Brooklyn (mentioned in context of Penn Track initiative)
keyFacts: The FBI New York Human Trafficking program is explicitly stated to be working on the 'highest profile HT cases in the FBI: i.e. Epstein, NXIVM, OneTaste.'
The FBI NY HT program is rated as a Band III threat and is described as a model for other field offices, being the only HT program rated 'High Performing' for each of the last 6 years.
The FBI NY Crimes Against Children program is rated as a Band II threat, with 70% of its 88 new FY23 investigations targeting Tier I/Tier II offenders.
The document is an internal FBI performance and threat assessment briefing from Fiscal Year 2023, directed to ADIC James Smith.
The NY field office runs a 'Penn Track' initiative in Brooklyn targeting high levels of sex trafficking and violent crime, generating 12 investigations targeting over 120 traffickers.
